04506nam a22006615i 9781487519186DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192018onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875191867 a10.3138/97814875191862doi  a(DE-B1597)525931  a(OCoLC)1102797915  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBR115.T42b.V363 2018 7aREL1160002bisacsh1 aVanderburg, Willem H., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSecular Nations under New Gods :bChristianity’s Subversion by Technology and Politics /cWillem H. Vanderburg. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (448 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Possibility and Impossibility of Living a Secular Life -- t2. The Roots of a Non-secular Life: Religion and Morality as Symptoms of Evil -- t3. Language, Myth, and History -- t4. Born Neither Free nor Equal, but Loved -- t5. The Law, the Spirit, and the Kingdom of Heaven -- t6. Christianity in the Grip of Vanity and Chasing after the Wind -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ongoing political muscle-flexing of diverse Christian communities in North America raises some deeply troubling questions regarding their roles among us. Earlier analyses including Herberg’s Protestant, Catholic, Jew showed that these three branches of the Judaeo-Christian tradition correspond to three forms of the American way of life; while Kruse’s One Nation Under God showed how Christian America was shaped by corporate America. Willem H. Vanderburg’s Secular Nations under New Gods proceeds based on a dialogue between Jacques Ellul’s interpretation of the task of Christians in the world and Ellul’s interpretation of the roles of technique and the nation-state in individual and collective human life. He then adds new insight into our being a symbolic species dealing with our finitude by living through the myths of our society and building new secular forms of moralities and religions. If everything is political and if everything is amenable to discipline-based scientific and technical approaches, we are perhaps treating these human creations the way earlier societies did their gods, as being omnipotent, without limits. Vanderburg argues that until organized Christianity becomes critically aware of sharing these commitments with their societies, it will remain entrapped in the service of false gods and thereby will continue to turn a message of freedom and love into one of morality and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aReligion and politics. 0aReligion and sociology. 0aTechnologyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aRELIGION / Religious Intolerance, Persecution & Conflict.2bisacsh  aChristianity.  aenslavement.  alimits.  amyths.  anon-religion.  apolitics.  ascience.  asecular.  asubversion of Christianity.  atechnology.1 aVanderburgh, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060679940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751918640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487519186423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487519186.jpg  a978-3-11-060679-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles